The therapeutic potential of exercise in post-traumatic stress disorder and its underlying mechanisms. Update 1.

Simonne Wright, Virginia Chiocchia

2025-05-17

Results

We identified ###### records. The PRISMA flow diagram is presented in Figure 1. A total of 13 studies with data from 852 participants were eligible for inclusion.The additional texts included secondary analyses, abstracts, trial registries, and protocol papers.

Table 1: Specific interventions for all the eligible studies

9 of the 13 studies were included in the meta-analyses (Bryant et al., 2023; Huseth, 2021; McGranahan et al., 2025; Nordbrandt et al., 2020; Rosenbaum et al., 2015; Voorendonk et al., 2023; Whitworth et al., 2019a; Whitworth et al., 2019b; Young-McCaughan et al., 2022). Meta-analysis was not feasible for 4 of the 13 studies (Ahar et al., 2024; Crombie et al., 2021; Greene & Petruzzello, 2022; Powers et al., 2015). Three studies examined putative mediators which was not sufficient to carry out a meta-analysis (Crombie et al., 2021; Powers et al., 2015; Whitworth et al., 2019a).

Study characteristics of the 9 studies included in the meta-analysis are presented in Table 2. From these 9 studies, there were 10 eligible comparisons. One study presented findings from two independent comparisons, including a total of four distinct intervention groups (Young-McCaughan et al., 2022). Additionally, one of the first authors published findings from two different but methodologically similar trials in the same year (Whitworth et al., 2019a; Whitworth et al., 2019b). Study characteristics of the 4 studies not included in the meta-analysis are are also presented in Table 2. One study provided two eligible exercise interventions groups and one control group (Greene & Petruzzello, 2022).

Primary outcome

PTSD Symptom Severity

Risk of bias for the PTSD symptom severity

The results of the risk of bias assessment per domain and study for the primary outcome, PTSD symptom severity is presented below in Figure 2. 10 studies reported PTSD outcome data post-intervention. Three studies did not report PTSD outcome data (Ahar et al., 2024; Crombie et al.,2021a; Greene & Petruzzello, 2022). Six of the nine studies had an overall high risk of bias, three had some concerns, and only one was had a low risk of bias. High risk of bias was mainly due to deviations from intended intervention (D2)(McGranahan et al., 2025; Voorendonk et al., 2023; Whitworth et al., 2019a;Whitworth et al., 2019b), missing outcome data (D3)(Rosenbaum et al., 2015; Voorendonk et al., 2023; Whitworth et al., 2019a; Whitworth et al.,2019b), and selection of reported results (D5)(Voorendonk et al., 2023; Young-McCaughan et al., 2022).

Figure 2: Results of the risk of bias assessment per domain and overall for the PTSD severity outcome

Post-intervention (weeks)

For the studies included in the meta-analyses, the earliest study was performed in 2014, while the most recent study was performed in 2025. The median sample size across the studies was 37 participants per study. The median of the mean participant age was 37 years (ranging from 29 to 50 years). Intervention length ranged from 3 to20 weeks, with a median of 8 weeks.

9 studies provided data for PTSD symptom severity and contributed 10 effect measures to the PTSD symptom severity meta-analysis. The forest plot for PTSD symptom severity is presented in Figure 3.

Figure 3: Meta-analysis of the effects of exercise on PTSD symptom severity.

The meta-analysis found some evidence of a difference in PTSD symptom severity reduction between exercise and comparison groups (SMD = -0.26, 95% CI -0.54 to 0.02). A τ² of 0.1104 and the prediction interval indicate the presence of between-study heterogeneity in the effect sizes.

Subgroup Analyses and Meta-regressions

Subgroup analysis by exercise intensity

The test for interaction found some evidence of a difference between studies with moderate intensity and those with high-intensity exercise (Figure 4). The effect of exercise appears to be larger in studies of high-intensity exercise compared to studies with moderate intensity

Figure 4: Sub-group analysis of the effects of exercise on PTSD symptom severity by exercise intensity

Subgroup analysis by specific exercise type

We did not find any important differences between the effects of aerobic, anaerobic, or mixed exercise groups (Figure 5).

Figure 5: Sub-group analysis of the effects of exercise on PTSD symptom severity by specific exercise type

Subgroup analysis by exercise alone or tau/therapy augmented by exercise.

Studies with exercise alone as intervention seemed to show larger effects than those in studies where patients were additionally given treatment-as-usual or psychotherapy (Figure 6).

Figure 6: Sub-group analysis of the effects of exercise on PTSD symptom severity by exercise alone or TAU/therapy augmented by exercise

Meta-regression by intervention length

We performed a meta-regression for the intervention duration, despite the fact that we had only 9 studies (Figure 7). The meta-regression analysis yielded a coefficient of 0.03 (95% CI: -0.02, 0.09), indicating that for every additional week, the standardized mean difference (SMD) in PTSD symptoms increased by 0.03. This suggests there was no meaningful association between intervention duration and PTSD symptom severity.

Sensitivity Analyses

Figure 8: Meta-analysis of the effects of exercise on PTSD symptom severity when excluding studies with high risk of bias

No evidence of a difference in treatment dropout between exercise and comparison groups (SMD = -0.11, 95% CI -0.31 to 0.1) was found when restricting the analysis to only studies with low or moderate risk of bias.

Reporting bias

Visual inspection of the contour-enhanced funnel plot did not suggest possible publication bias in favour the of exercise group.

Figure 9: Contour-enhanced funnel plot assessing publication bias

Small-study effects were assessed using Egger’s regression test for funnel plot asymmetry. The test suggested potential asymmetry in the funnel plot (p-value = .095) although the contour-enhanced funnel plot does not indicate publication bias as a source for it. The estimated bias coefficient was -1.96, 1.04, indicating that smaller studies may be associated with larger effect sizes.

Secondary outcomes

Study dropout (weeks)

9 studies provided data for study dropout, and contributed 10 effect measures to the meta-analysis. The forest plot for the risk of dropout is presented in Figure 10.

Figure 10: Meta-analysis of the dropout rates between the intervention and control groups

No evidence of a difference in dropout between exercise and comparison groups (RR = 1.28, 95% CI 0.73 to 2.26) was found and there was large heterogeneity, as shown by the prediction interval (0.22 to 7.49).

Summary of Evidence
